Url.Title: Welcome to Volusion Themes
Url.Abstract: Welcome to Volusion Themes Storefronts and company websites have become far more interactive experiences for shoppers, accessed on a variety of devices, mobile phones, and computers. Volusion sees the trends and has incorporated new opportunities to match your business with the latest technologies. You can add new responsive themes to your storefronts, powered by a theme engine and supported with a REST Storefront API.

Url.Title: Prepping the Environment
Url.Abstract: Prepping the Environment The first step is to prepare your environment for modifying and creating your masterpieces of code and design. You can use Mac OS X+ or Windows 7/8+ systems to install the tools required for the framework and code. If you are unfamiliar with these tools, not to worry! Every installation step includes instructions and links to more information for every tool.

Url.Title: Step 1: Install GitHub If you have a GitHub account, continue to step 2.
Url.Abstract: Step 1: Install GitHub If you have a GitHub account, continue to step 2. GitHub is the source control code repository for all Volusion Themes. You can install the GitHub client to download, sync, and update your theme code. All available Volusion Themes are available through GitHub.

Url.Title: Step 2: Install Node.jsIf you have Node.js installed, continue to step 3.
Url.Abstract: Step 2: Install Node.jsIf you have Node.js installed, continue to step 3. Node.js is the JavaScript framework used to develop and support Volusion Themes. The framework is an event driven, non-blocking I/O model for lightweight and efficient development for scalable network programming. Node is similar to Ruby's Event Machine and Python's Twisted for the seasoned web developer, while extending the event loop itself as a language construct rather than a typical library.

Url.Title: Step 3: Install RubyIf you have Ruby installed, review the instructions for tools, gems, and scripts. Next, install Compass with step 4.
Url.Abstract: Step 3: Install RubyIf you have Ruby installed, review the instructions for tools, gems, and scripts. Next, install Compass with step 4.

Url.Title: Step 4: Install Sass and CompassIf you have the Compass gem installed, continue to Bootstrap or Postman.
Url.Abstract: Step 4: Install Sass and CompassIf you have the Compass gem installed, continue to Bootstrap or Postman.

Url.Title: Download a Volusion Theme
Url.Abstract: Download a Volusion Theme We designed the Theme Engine with three main goals: to give you unlimited creatity, with incredible features built-in, and access to a powerful API to build that site you've been dreaming of.

Url.Title: Install Apps and PluginsAdd optional apps and plugins to test API calls and preview themes.
Url.Abstract: Install Apps and PluginsAdd optional apps and plugins to test API calls and preview themes. We recommend the following plugins, apps, and extensions for your web development:

Url.Title: Customizing Your Theme
Url.Abstract: Customizing Your Theme You can begin creating a theme for the theme engine from scratch, or you can get a copy of a seed project from the Volusion Theme Engine GitHub. For details on installing the theme, see Download a Volusion Theme.

Url.Title: Theme Folder StructureA quick overview of where files are.
Url.Abstract: Theme Folder StructureA quick overview of where files are. After you have created a copy of the theme files from GitHub (by clone, branch, fork or other method), you can begin digging into the files and customizing the theme formats.

Url.Title: Storefront Theme Page Usage
Url.Abstract: Storefront Theme Page Usage Adding a responsive theme to your store changes specific pages to become "theme-specific". This means, specific pages load the customized responsive theme layouts, formats, styles, and content over the legacy templates you previously used for your store. Each customized responsive theme may affect these pages differently, depending on the designed content, styles, and web components.

Url.Title: Storefront Style Overview
Url.Abstract: Storefront Style Overview Styles are a powerful, immediate way to add customization and branding flair to your storefront. Styles typically have been a series of formatting selections, documented as code within a CSS file (cascading style sheet) that enforced a single view site-wide. Through the CSS file(s), you could design and maintain the exact look and feel you want for all text content, display controls such as tables and menus, and assets such as images and videos all from a single controlled place.

Url.Title: Adding and Using Fonts
Url.Abstract: Adding and Using Fonts Typography is one of the most widely used content and important pieces in any webpage and site. Fonts can provide a facelift, increasing legible reading online and for print of your text. You can use incredible fonts and text not only to provide descriptions and headings, but also lends to logo design, product images, and creative backgrounds.

Url.Title: Custom Translations
Url.Abstract: Custom Translations Every theme provides support for custom text per page and multiple translations of your storefront. You can create as many language files as you need per language through the themes.

Url.Title: Image Spriting
Url.Abstract: Image Spriting

Url.Title: Sass Sprite Maps
Url.Abstract: Sass Sprite Maps You can create any size of image to use as a sprite, as a jpg, svg, or png, for use in your theme. Maps give you the ability to add multiple images all matching in dimensions into a single image for use within SCSS files to insert into your page templates.

Url.Title: Designing with Storefront APIs
Url.Abstract: Designing with Storefront APIs The Method theme gives an example of invoking Storefront APIs through the JavaScript files in the various scripts sub-folders and files. These files are located in the {your repo}\method\app\scripts\ folder. Not all files and folders are listed. But this information should give you a guideline for how the Method theme makes calls and the API is used.

Url.Title: Theme Management
Url.Abstract: Theme Management As you create your responsive themes, you can save that content to GitHub. Volusion will provide a Marketplace service for offering your themes to all merchants and designers. The repository is also accessed when uploading the theme for your Admin designs.

Url.Title: Inside the Storefront API
Url.Abstract: Inside the Storefront API Everything you need to build unique storefront experiences is available through the Volusion Storefront API. This API provides public endpoints to retrieve data from your store, update changed carts and orders, validate carts and users, and support new features you create through apps and widgets. Create new and exciting responsive themes for your storefront, extending and interacting with these APIs. Build new apps and widgets that take Volusion features beyond anything seen before. The possibilities continue to extend and enhance as endpoint development continues at Volusion.

Url.Title: Requirements
Url.Abstract: Requirements The following information guides you through the information, tools and skills you will need for working with the Volusion Storefront API.

Url.Title: Response Status Codes
Url.Abstract: Response Status Codes When you make a JSON request, a status code responds to state the success or failure of the action. These codes differ according to the type of request made to the API. In the returned JSON response, a message may be included with further information regarding the code.

Url.Title: Request Format
Url.Abstract: Request Format When contacting the API for data to perform actions, you will send a request to the VolusionREST API endpoints. The request will receive a response of a status code and a JSON response envelope of data.

Url.Title: REST API Endpoints
Url.Abstract: REST API Endpoints The following is a detailed list of all REST API endpoints in the Storefront API. When entering a request, you will follow a specific format. For details, learn more about the request structure content and response data. Each listed API includes a link to further information, sample JSON requests and responses, and in-depth information for the implementation of your code.

Url.Title: Categories Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Categories Endpoint The categories endpoint supports getting specific information about one category or a collection of categories. These categories represent a main category, a subcategory, or a specific category page to load and display in the storefront. Products are associated to one or more categories and subcategories, depending on the grouping decisions you want displayed within the storefront. Top level categories are also assigned to specific navigation menu locations, acting as the top named buttons that have drop-down categories and subcategories for browsing. These groupings give shoppers a browsing experience for locating products in your store, viewing related products, and sharing an entire group of products with friends on social media and via email.

Url.Title: Get Components
Url.Abstract: Get Components This GET method retrieves a collection of all components available and in-use on the storefront. These objects are web components for use in sites to generate custom HTML and CSS interactions and design on a site. Common examples of components in the Volusion Storefront include a slider for image and content across the top of a web page and an area for displaying shopper reviews.

Url.Title: Get a Collection of All Categories
Url.Abstract: Get a Collection of All Categories This GET method requests all categories for the storefront. In turn, the response contains a collection for every category-to-subcategory-to-subcategory matching the parent-to-child relationship of categories. The nesting of categories can continue and return a large amount of data entirely dependent on the category hierarchy you have designed in your storefront.

Url.Title: Product Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Product Endpoint The product endpoint supports getting specific information about one product or a collection of products. These products represent items sold through the store, be it physical items to ship from a warehouse to a downloadable file. When requesting product objects, you can enter the category ID products are associated to, a filter for reducing and focusing the returned list of data in the collection, and pagination information. The returned JSON includes a collection of product objects, including the product code, name, prices, descriptions, SEO content, and additional information for use in your implementations.

Url.Title: Get a Specific Product
Url.Abstract: Get a Specific Product This GET method retrieves a specific product's data. The method allows you to enter a specific product code, which you entered when creating the product. The returned JSON includes only the data for that product object in the store. The request does not need to include any other parameters such as for obtaining an array of products.

Url.Title: Get a Collection of All Products
Url.Abstract: Get a Collection of All Products This GET method requests and receives all possible products in the store. Depending on the size of the store, the amount could be extensive. To refine the returned results, the request can specify specific categories, search terms, facets, minimum and maximum price, accessories, sorting and pagination for a limited set of all products.

Url.Title: Get Product Reviews
Url.Abstract: Get Product Reviews This GET method retrieves the available reviews for a specific product. The method allows you to enter a specific product code to retrieve shopper entered review comments and ratings. These reviews in turn could be highlighted with design, page layouts, and additional app functionality for enhancing shopper purchases. The resulting data includes numerical ratings, a number of total reviews for the product, and all specific reviews by poster, rating, content written, the number of shoppers finding it as helpful, and posted date.

Url.Title: Articles Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Articles Endpoint The articles endpoint supports getting a list of all available articles in your store. Articles are content "pages" or sections of content (text and images with formatting) created and maintained through the Admin and displayed through the storefront. Great examples of an article include help pages, history of your company, the About Us content, and return policies. If you provide products that need instructions for downloading, using, or even building, you could use these articles to provide that content. Or you may want to add pages to the storefront on your return policies and shipping options.

Url.Title: Get a List of Articles
Url.Abstract: Get a List of Articles This GET method requests a full list of articles from your store. The response will provide a list of articles including the ID, title, body and SEO settings. Depending on the amount of articles you create and use in your store, the response may be lengthy with content.

Url.Title: Navigation Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Navigation Endpoint The navigation endpoint supports getting all associated categories linked to a navigation menu in the storefront. Each navigation menu includes a main category with subcategories displayed below or beside. The layout and design of the theme greatly determines the display and flow of these navigation locations. With this method, you can enter the ID for one of eight navigation menus to receive a collection of the associated categories and subcategories linked to the location. The response JSON may be lengthy depending on the hierarchy of category and subcategory nesting on your storefront.

Url.Title: Get Navigation Links
Url.Abstract: Get Navigation Links This GET method requests a full list of all links for a navigation area of the storefront. The response provides a list of all categories with subcategories linked to the input navigation area by numbered location. The storefront supports up to eight navigation menus that display across the top of side depending on the design of your theme. Depending on the depth of subcategories in your category hierarchy, the response may be lengthy.

Url.Title: Config Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Config Endpoint The articles endpoint supports getting a list of all available articles in your store. Site configuration data includes information entered on the site storefront (site title, logo, etc.), SEO settings, specifics for shopper checkout and additional data as provided and configured. You can enter and update this content directly through the Admin via a number of pages and options, including Settings and Marketing menus.

Url.Title: Get the Site Config
Url.Abstract: Get the Site Config This GET method requests site configuration content entered through the Admin. The response provides a list of configuration settings and values for the storefront site. This data does not include every single configuration option available. For a full list of options and settings, review the Admin in the Settings > Config Variables page.

Url.Title: Components Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Components Endpoint The components endpoint supports getting a list of components currently in use or available to your storefront. A web component is a custom HTML element used in websites for use in design or providing unique content in innovative ways. Components encapsulate HTML, CSS, and addition code interactions. A common example of a web component is a slider for images, text, videos, and additional content with links to site locations to display through visitor interactions or on a timed loop.

Url.Title: Get Components
Url.Abstract: Get Components This GET method retrieves a collection of all components available and in-use on the storefront. These objects are web components for use in sites to generate custom HTML and CSS interactions and design on a site. Common examples of components in the Volusion Storefront include a slider for image and content across the top of a web page and an area for displaying shopper reviews.

Url.Title: Carts Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Carts Endpoint The carts endpoint supports multiple methods for getting, adding items, updating, and deleting shopping carts. Carts encapsulate all items and elements of an order in-progress. The data associated with a cart includes the items added to the cart by the shopper and all checkout details. Checkout details include billing address, shipping address, and payment profile data.

Url.Title: Get a Cart
Url.Abstract: Get a Cart This GET method requests a shopper's cart. The endpoint receives the cart ID from the cookie for the shopper. The response only provides a subset of cart objects: the cart item object and the cart totals object. Depending on the in-progress status of the shopper's experience, information returned on a GET includes NULL data. As the process moves from adding items to cart into the checkout stage, the data returns updates with more information available.

Url.Title: Add a Product to a Cart
Url.Abstract: Add a Product to a Cart To add a product to the shopper's cart, you use a POSTmethod. You can add a product using the product code, quantity being purchased, and any configured options available and requested for that product. The endpoint receives the cart ID from the cookie for the shopper, not requiring the cart ID for the method. The response only provides a 201 status code on success.

Url.Title: Update a Cart
Url.Abstract: Update a Cart This PUT method updates new data and configurations to the current cart for the shopper. Unlike the POST method to add a product, this method updates specific information for the cart and current items in the cart. You can update the item, discount, shipping address, shipping method, payment profile, billing address, miscellaneous, custom field, and customer attributes.

Url.Title: Delete a Cart
Url.Abstract: Delete a Cart The DELETEmethod is used when deleting the entire cart object, best used when the order has been placed and enters the processing stage (post-checkout). You do not want to delete the cart prior to final payment submission as the shopper may want to change a quantity for a product or add another product to the cart during the checkout process. The response only provides a 204 status code on success.

Url.Title: Countries Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Countries Endpoint The countries endpoint provides the supported countries and associated states or provinces available in the storefront. These countries and states are used for addresses, and aid in determining taxes and shipping costs.

Url.Title: Get Countries
Url.Abstract: Get Countries This GET method requests a full list of all supported countries and their states or provinces. These values are used throughout the storefront checkout processes for any address entered and used by the system. The response includes a country with a collection of states or provinces for that country. If multiple countries are supported, the response will include nested attributes for the country object and its collection.

Url.Title: Users Endpoint
Url.Abstract: Users Endpoint The users endpoint provides methods to create and update user accounts within the system and storefront. These user accounts typically are shoppers, with associated shipping addresses, billing addresses, and payment profiles per their ID. The endpoint also includes methods for verifying if an account already exists for the entered email and if the user is logged in currently.

Url.Title: Create a User
Url.Abstract: Create a User This POST method provides user data to create an account in the storefront. The entered data is saved as records for a specific, newly generated ID. This ID links all user information and actions for adding and modifying information, including shipping addresses, billing addresses, and payment profiles. The response includes a 201 status code and the new ID.

Url.Title: Check Email
Url.Abstract: Check Email This GET method determines if the passed email address has an account currently in the storefront. If the email has been used, a 200 status code returns. This indicates an account exists for the email address. A new account cannot be created. If the email is not in the system, a 404 status code returns. This indicates an account does not exist. The email address can be used for creating a new user account.

Url.Title: Get Logged In User
Url.Abstract: Get Logged In User This GET method requests the information for the currently logged in user account on the storefront. The response includes the user account ID, full name, and email address. You can use this content to determine who is logged in, and use that ID to gain further user account information or provide additional services per the logged in user.

Url.Title: Response Format
